"use strict";(self.webpackChunkdoeks_website=self.webpackChunkdoeks_website||[]).push([["6607"],{77735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852","source":"@site/blog/visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852.mdx","title":"Visualizing Istio: Why I Built Interactive Simulations for Traffic Management","description":"banner","date":"2025-12-22T15:07:49.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Service Mesh","permalink":"/blog/tags/service-mesh"}],"readingTime":1.34,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Visualizing Istio: Why I Built Interactive Simulations for Traffic Management","slug":"visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852","date":"2025-12-22T15:07:49.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*cntFmNr0Ud5ymwm1YWz9AA.jpeg","tags":["Service Mesh"]},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Solution Architect! Art of Disaster Recovery (DR)","permalink":"/blog/solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*cntFmNr0Ud5ymwm1YWz9AA.jpeg)\\n\\n\\n\\nMoving beyond the terminal to master Blue/Green and Canary deployments in a Cloud-Native world.\\n\\n### The \u201CBlack Box\u201D\xa0Problem\\n\\nIn the world of Kubernetes, Service Meshes like **Istio** are often treated as \u201Cmagic.\u201D We apply a VirtualService YAML, change a weight from 0 to 10, and trust that traffic is moving correctly behind the\xa0scenes.\\n\\nBut for many engineers, this remains a black box. When a Canary rollout fails or a Blue/Green switch causes a spike in 500 errors, the lack of **visual intuition** can lead to slow incident response\xa0times.\\n\\nAs the founder of **Kubelancer**, I\u2019ve seen teams struggle with the \u201Cconceptual gap\u201D of traffic shifting. Understanding the theory is one thing; seeing a packet hit a VirtualService and get routed to a specific pod version is\xa0another.\\n\\nThat\u2019s why I decided to build **Kubelancer Labs**\u200A\u2014\u200Aa zero-setup, interactive playground to simulate Istio traffic\xa0logic.\\n\\n#### What can you do in the\xa0lab?\\n\\nYou can visualize the traffic management\\n\\nBlue/Green: Switch traffic instantly and practice emergency rollbacks.\\n\\nCanary Rollouts: Incrementally shift traffic (10% \u2192 50% \u2192 100%) and watch the pods\xa0react.\\n\\nFault Simulation: Trigger \u201C500 Errors\u201D to see how Istio protects the user experience.\\n\\nNo terminal. No YAML. Just pure logic and visualization.\\n\\n#### Check it out live\xa0here:\\n\\n#### \u{1F449} [https://bala-kubelancer.github.io/kubelancer-labs-simulations/](https://bala-kubelancer.github.io/kubelancer-labs-simulations/)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=c366bb60b852)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10","source":"@site/blog/solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10.mdx","title":"Solution Architect! Art of Disaster Recovery (DR)","description":"banner","date":"2025-12-22T11:57:01.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":1.85,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Solution Architect! Art of Disaster Recovery (DR)","slug":"solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10","date":"2025-12-22T11:57:01.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*Wx_tEOyINsNH9D1mCzWLUQ.jpeg","tags":[]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Visualizing Istio: Why I Built Interactive Simulations for Traffic Management","permalink":"/blog/visualizing-istio-why-i-built-interactive-simulations-for-traffic-management-c366bb60b852"},"nextItem":{"title":"Which load balancer is best for microservices on AWS EKS?","permalink":"/blog/which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*Wx_tEOyINsNH9D1mCzWLUQ.jpeg)\\n\\n\\n\\nEnsuring Business Continuity in a Crisis. In today\u2019s digital-first world, High Availability (HA) and Fault Tolerance (FT) are designed to keep applications up and running. But what if an entire region goes down due to a flood or a power grid outage, or other\xa0reasons?\\n\\nThis is where a Disaster Recovery (DR) strategy becomes critical for ensuring business continuity. A well-designed DR plan ensures sufficient resources are available in entirely different regions, countries, or even continents.\\n\\n### RTO and RPO: The Foundation of DR\xa0Planning\\n\\n\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\u200A\u2014\\n\\n**When planning DR, two key metrics must be defined:**  \\n\\\\============================================  \\n1\\\\. Recovery Time Objective (RTO): How much downtime a business can sustain without significant impact.\\n\\n2\\\\. Recovery Point Objective (RPO): How much data loss a business can tolerate.\\n\\nThe design of RTO and RPO depends on business criticality.\\n\\n**_For example:_**  \\nA stock trading platform, railway system, or airline booking system cannot afford to lose a single data\xa0point.\\n\\n#### **DR Approaches:**  \\n\\\\=============\\n\\n\u2014 **Backup &\xa0Restore:**\\n\\nThe least costly option with maximum RTO and RPO.  \\nApplication machine images and database snapshots should be stored in the DR site.  \\nIn the event of DR, systems are restored from\xa0backups.\\n\\n**\u2014 Warm\xa0Standby:**\\n\\nAll application servers and databases exist in the DR site with low capacity.  \\nData is continuously synced from the primary.  \\nIn case of DR, services can be scaled up at the DR site.  \\nOffers lower RTO and RPO compared to backup &\xa0restore.\\n\\n**\u2014 Multi-Site (Active-Active):**\\n\\nMost advanced and resilient DR strategy.  \\nProvides zero RTO and RPO.  \\nEqual capacity is maintained at both sites.  \\nTraffic is distributed across regions.  \\nIn case of failure, all traffic is routed locally without downtime.\\n\\n**Final Thoughts:**  \\n\\\\============  \\nA robust Disaster Recovery plan is not just about technology\u200A\u2014\u200Ait\u2019s about protecting your business, customers, and reputation. The choice between Backup & Restore, Warm Standby, and Multi-Site depends on business needs, compliance, and\xa0cost.\\n\\n**Ask yourself:**  \\n\\\\============  \\nHow much downtime can your business afford? (RTO)  \\nHow much data loss can your business tolerate? (RPO)\\n\\n### :) Happy Computing\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=dc8a860f4e10)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb","source":"@site/blog/which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb.mdx","title":"Which load balancer is best for microservices on AWS EKS?","description":"banner","date":"2025-12-05T05:56:10.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"AWS","permalink":"/blog/tags/aws"},{"inline":true,"label":"Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/tags/kubernetes"}],"readingTime":1.64,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Which load balancer is best for microservices on AWS EKS?","slug":"which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb","date":"2025-12-05T05:56:10.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*JLJollfy1IgkT9YqvRSS5Q.png","tags":["AWS","Kubernetes"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Solution Architect! Art of Disaster Recovery (DR)","permalink":"/blog/solution-architect-art-of-disaster-recovery-dr-dc8a860f4e10"},"nextItem":{"title":"How I Build Scalable, Secure, and Reliable Cloud Systems","permalink":"/blog/how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*JLJollfy1IgkT9YqvRSS5Q.png)\\n\\n\\n\\n#### Short answer up\xa0front:\\n\\n\\\\* **Use ALB** (AWS Application Load Balancer) at the edge for almost all HTTP/HTTPS microservices workloads. _It gives host/path routing, TLS offload, WebACL/WAF, and better request-level features that microservices typically need._\\n\\n\\\\* **Use NLB** only when you need true L4 passthrough, extremely low latency very high connection scale, UDP/TCP workloads, or when preserving source IP is critical and simpler setup is preferred.\\n\\n\\\\* **Hybrid (ALB at edge + internal NLB)** is a great compromise when you need ALB features at the edge but want NLB performance for specific internal high-throughput services.\\n\\n#### Why microservices usually favour ALB\xa0?\\n\\nMicroservices architectures typically expose many small HTTP/HTTPS services, use host- and path-based routing (e.g., [api.example.com/users](http://api.example.com/users), [api.example.com/payments](http://api.example.com/payments)), use TLS, and often require features\xa0like:\\n\\n\u2014 per-host routing (virtual hosts)  \\n\u200A\u2014\u200Apath-based routing and rewriting  \\n\u200A\u2014\u200ATLS termination with ACM and easy certificate management  \\n\u200A\u2014\u200AWeb Application Firewall (WAF) protections at the edge  \\n\u200A\u2014\u200AHTTP features: websockets, HTTP/2, header manipulation, redirect rules  \\neasy integration with Gateway API for Kubernetes-native routing  \\n_ALB provides all of these natively._\\n\\n#### When to pick NLB\xa0instead?\\n\\nPick NLB when one of the following is\xa0true:\\n\\n\u2014 Your services are TCP/UDP (non-HTTP) or need pure L4 passthrough. Examples: raw TCP proxies, some legacy protocols, high-volume TCP streaming.\\n\\n\u2014 You need lowest possible latency and the highest concurrent connection scale (NLB is optimized for\xa0L4).\\n\\n\u2014 You want simple Service annotation deployment without installing AWS Load Balancer Controller (fast\xa0setup).\\n\\n\u2014 You want to preserve source client IP easily and reliably for backend services.\\n\\nNLB is simpler for L4 and usually cheaper for pure throughput scenarios, but it lacks L7 routing and\xa0WAF.\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=2c9f64b853eb)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21","source":"@site/blog/how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21.mdx","title":"How I Build Scalable, Secure, and Reliable Cloud Systems","description":"banner","date":"2025-10-31T12:33:15.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":4.79,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"How I Build Scalable, Secure, and Reliable Cloud Systems","slug":"how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21","date":"2025-10-31T12:33:15.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*c046O54TWqJo-5nr5AJ3dg.png","tags":[]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Which load balancer is best for microservices on AWS EKS?","permalink":"/blog/which-load-balancer-is-best-for-microservices-on-aws-eks-2c9f64b853eb"},"nextItem":{"title":"Getting credentials: exec: executable aws failed with exit code 255","permalink":"/blog/getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*c046O54TWqJo-5nr5AJ3dg.png)\\n\\n\\n\\nOver the decades of working as a Cloud and DevOps Architect, I\u2019ve realized that this role is not just about technology\u200A\u2014\u200Ait\u2019s about building reliable, scalable, and secure systems that truly support business\xa0goals.\\n\\nToday, organizations expect Cloud plus DevOps architects like us to balance innovation with practicality, design with delivery, and speed with stability.\\n\\nEvery design choice impacts how well a system performs, scales, and recovers\u200A\u2014\u200Aand how safe it keeps business\xa0data.\\n\\nSome of the key habits I lean in every day professional life\\n\\n### Try to understand the Business Problem, how to suit the right technology and\xa0tools\\n\\nBefore choosing a tool or platform, I first try to understand the\xa0_why_.\\n\\nEvery technical decision\u200A\u2014\u200Afrom infrastructure to automation\u200A\u2014\u200Amust align with business needs such as cost, scalability, and timelines.\\n\\n_As a Cloud Architect, my job is to provide solutions that solve real business problems while handling constraints like budget, compliance, and delivery schedules._\\n\\n### Address Project Non-Functional Needs\\n\\nBeyond functionality, I always design for what\u2019s _not visible_ but _critical_:\\n\\n*   **Scalability**\u200A\u2014\u200ACan it grow seamlessly when demand\xa0spikes?\\n*   **High availability**\u200A\u2014\u200AWill it stay up if something fails?\\n*   **Performance**\u200A\u2014\u200ADoes it respond fast under pressure?\\n*   **Security**\u200A\u2014\u200AIs data safe at every\xa0layer?\\n*   **Maintainability**\u200A\u2014\u200ACan teams manage it easily\xa0later?\\n\\n_These non-functional aspects often define whether a system succeeds in the long\xa0run._\\n\\n### Use Prototypes and Proofs of Concept\xa0(POCs)\\n\\nBefore going full scale, I generally build prototypes to validate the design approach.\\n\\n_This helps me and my team identify risks early, test assumptions, and ensure we are choosing the right strategy before major investments are\xa0made._\\n\\n### Don\u2019t Just Build Systems, Also Mentor\xa0Teams\\n\\nTechnology evolves fast, and so should the people behind\xa0it.\\n\\n_I work closely with developers, operations, and security engineers to ensure everyone understands the \u201Cwhy\u201D behind design decisions & how to maintain those systems post-launch._\\n\\n### Balance Strategy and Operations\\n\\nBeing an architect means thinking both long-term and day-to-day.\\n\\n*   **Strategic View:** Create solutions that remain relevant as technology and business\xa0evolve.\\n*   **Operational View:** Ensure today\u2019s workloads run smoothly and handle current business challenges without\xa0issues.\\n\\n_It\u2019s this balance that turns architecture into\xa0value._\\n\\n### Design with Compliance and Global Reach in\xa0Mind\\n\\nWhen deploying globally, every region comes with its own laws and compliance requirements.\\n\\nWhether it\u2019s **PCI DSS** for finance, **HIPAA** for healthcare, or **ISO** standards for manufacturing\xa0\u2026many more, compliance has to be baked into design\u200A\u2014\u200Anot added\xa0later.\\n\\nPlan for:\\n\\n*   Data locality and residency laws\\n*   Encryption (in transit and at\xa0rest)\\n*   Identity and access management (IAM)\\n*   Secure audit logging and traceability\\n\\n_Compliance isn\u2019t paperwork\u200A\u2014\u200Ait\u2019s part of security architecture._\\n\\n### Tighten the Security at Every Layer of\xa0infra\\n\\nSecurity is a continuous process, not a one-time\xa0setup.\\n\\nI design with the principle of **least privilege**, and integrate security into every phase of development and operation.\\n\\nKey practices I rely\xa0on:\\n\\n*   Enforce IAM roles and fine-grained permissions\\n*   Use secret managers and encrypted storage\\n*   Automate patching and vulnerability scanning\\n*   Implement Web Application Firewalls (WAF) and security\xa0groups\\n*   Enable audit logging, SIEM integration, and intrusion detection\\n*   Adopt shift-left security\u200A\u2014\u200Aembedding security checks in\xa0CI/CD\\n\\n_Security must evolve with the application\u200A\u2014\u200Anot lag behind\xa0it._\\n\\n### Automate Everything as much as\xa0Possible\\n\\nAutomation is at the heart of both Cloud and DevOps practices.\\n\\nAutomation applies everywhere\u200A\u2014\u200Ainfrastructure provisioning, deployments, testing, patching, and even security\xa0checks.\\n\\nAs a DevOps Architect, I\xa0ensure:\\n\\n*   **Infrastructure as Code (IaC)** manages resources predictably.\\n*   **CI/CD pipelines** are robust and reliable.\\n*   **Automated security scans** and policy enforcement\\n*   **Automated rollback and self-healing** mechanisms\\n*   **Monitoring and alerts** automatically notify teams about issues or failures.\\n\\n_It helps reduce human error, increase speed, and maintain consistency._\\n\\n### Ensure End-to-End Monitoring and Observability\\n\\nA system you can\u2019t see is a system you can\u2019t\xa0trust.\\n\\nI make sure every deployment includes:\\n\\n*   **Centralized logging** (application + infrastructure)\\n*   **Metrics collection** (CPU, memory, latency, request\xa0rate)\\n*   **Alerting and dashboards** using tools like Prometheus, Grafana, and New\xa0Relic\\n*   **Distributed tracing** for performance bottlenecks\\n*   **Synthetic monitoring** for uptime and user experience\\n\\n_Monitoring is the backbone of reliability\u200A\u2014\u200Ait helps teams act before customers notice\xa0issues._\\n\\n### Keep an eye regularly on Cloud Cost\xa0Page\\n\\nEvery solution has a cost\u200A\u2014\u200Aboth upfront (CapEx) and ongoing\xa0(OpEx).\\n\\n_As part of my process, I provide clear cost estimations, help plan budgets, and continuously optimize infrastructure to reduce waste and improve efficiency._\\n\\n### Design for Resilience and Disaster\xa0Recovery\\n\\nDowntime is never an option. From day one, I plan for\xa0failure.\\n\\nSystems should recover automatically or gracefully during incidents.\\n\\nI define:\\n\\n*   **RPO (Recovery Point Objective):** How much data can we afford to\xa0lose?\\n*   **RTO (Recovery Time Objective):** How fast can we\xa0recover?\\n*   **Backup and failover strategies** across\xa0regions\\n*   **Testing DR drills** regularly to validate recovery\xa0plans\\n\\nBecause resilience isn\u2019t proven in design\u200A\u2014\u200Ait\u2019s proven in a disaster.\\n\\nSo plan for both **RPO (Recovery Point Objective)** and **RTO (Recovery Time Objective)** from day\xa0one.\\n\\n_That means preparing for data recovery, failover systems, and having tested backup strategies\u200A\u2014\u200Aensuring the business stays operational even during\xa0outages._\\n\\n### Continuously Optimize and\xa0Evolve\\n\\nCloud technology changes\xa0daily.\\n\\nI make it a habit to continuously explore new features from AWS, Azure, and\xa0GCP\\n\\n\u2014 applying what fits best to improve cost, performance, and reliability.\\n\\n\u2014 Continuous improvement isn\u2019t just a technical habit\u200A\u2014\u200Ait\u2019s a\xa0mindset.\\n\\n_Good architecture is invisible when it works, but invaluable when it\xa0fails._\\n\\n### Happy Cloud Computing\xa0:)\\n\\n_Thanks for\xa0reading!_\\n\\nFollow me on \\\\[LinkedIn\\\\] [https://www.linkedin.com/in/bala-kubelancer/](https://www.linkedin.com/in/bala-kubelancer/)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=101af18edc21)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f","source":"@site/blog/getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f.mdx","title":"Getting credentials: exec: executable aws failed with exit code 255","description":"banner","date":"2025-07-01T15:56:14.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"AWS","permalink":"/blog/tags/aws"}],"readingTime":1.19,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Getting credentials: exec: executable aws failed with exit code 255","slug":"getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f","date":"2025-07-01T15:56:14.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*bI5us0H7TVdGRgc-1MXP9Q.png","tags":["AWS"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"How I Build Scalable, Secure, and Reliable Cloud Systems","permalink":"/blog/how-i-build-scalable-secure-and-reliable-cloud-systems-101af18edc21"},"nextItem":{"title":"Optimizing AWS EKS with Karpenter: A Hybrid Instance Strategy","permalink":"/blog/optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*bI5us0H7TVdGRgc-1MXP9Q.png)\\n\\n\\n\\nError: failed to create kubernetes rest client for read of resource: Get \u201Chttps://xxxxxxx.gr7.us-east-1.eks.amazonaws.com/api?timeout=32s\\": getting credentials: exec: executable aws failed with exit code\xa0255\\n\\nMost Terraform users might have seen this 255 error. Suddenly, for some reason, Terraform will surprise us specifically in\xa0AWS.\\n\\nLet\u2019s **break down exactly what\u2019s happening**:\\n\\nThe problem is mostly with Terraform; try using your local kubeconfig to connect to\xa0EKS.\\n\\nWhat happened generally?\\n\\nkubernetes/kubectl/helm provider execute aws eks get-token to get a short-lived authentication token, but it can\u2019t get it due to a few\xa0reasons\\n\\nNo Kubernetes REST client could be\xa0created\\n\\n1.  could be an issue on AWS credentials\\n2.  If CI/CD, credential env not set correctly/wrongly\\n3.  Your ~/.aws/config or ~/.aws/credentials is missing or\xa0invalid.\\n\\nLet\u2019s Troubleshoot\\n\\nTry this in your\xa0shell:\\n\\n```\\naws eks get-token --cluster-name your-cluster-name\\n```\\n\\nIf this fails, you\u2019ll get a clearer\xa0error.\\n\\nIn my case, it worked. Next, I did If you\u2019re using profiles, set:\\n\\n```\\nexport_ AWS\\\\_PROFILE=your-profile\\n```\\n\\nexport_ AWS\\\\_PROFILE=kubelancer-dev\\n\\nwhich solved.\\n\\nthen try\\n\\n```\\nterraform plan  \\nterraform apply\\n```\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=e0c15e8c081f)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292","source":"@site/blog/optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292.mdx","title":"Optimizing AWS EKS with Karpenter: A Hybrid Instance Strategy","description":"banner","date":"2025-02-24T15:10:57.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"AWS","permalink":"/blog/tags/aws"},{"inline":true,"label":"Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/tags/kubernetes"}],"readingTime":2.77,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Optimizing AWS EKS with Karpenter: A Hybrid Instance Strategy","slug":"optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292","date":"2025-02-24T15:10:57.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/960/1*AbM1f-rB7GULfHceKajtYg.png","tags":["AWS","Kubernetes"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Getting credentials: exec: executable aws failed with exit code 255","permalink":"/blog/getting-credentials-exec-executable-aws-failed-with-exit-code-255-e0c15e8c081f"},"nextItem":{"title":"Path Based - Simple Fanout Ingress on Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/960/1*AbM1f-rB7GULfHceKajtYg.png)\\n\\n\\n\\nAs Kubernetes adoption grows, so does the complexity of managing clusters efficiently. One common challenge is choosing the right EC2 instance types that balance performance, cost, and availability. Enter **Karpenter**, AWS\u2019s open-source cluster autoscaler, designed to simplify and optimize Kubernetes infrastructure provisioning.\\n\\nIn this blog post, How Kubelancer, we implemented **hybrid instance strategy** using **Karpenter** on **AWS EKS Cluster for our esteemed client**, ton maximize performance while minimizing costs in production, if non-prod can think about spot\xa0fleet.\\n\\n**Generally, Karpenter** addresses these challenges:\\n\\n**1\\\\. Rapid provisioning:** Instantly launching nodes when\xa0needed.\\n\\n**2\\\\. Cost optimization:** Choosing the most cost-effective instance\xa0types.\\n\\n**3\\\\. Workload-aware scaling:** Allocating resources based on real-time workload requirements.\\n\\n**4\\\\. Support for Spot Instances:** Reducing costs further by leveraging EC2 Spot Instances.\\n\\n> _But how can we unlock its full potential?_ **_Hybrid instance strategies_** _hold the\xa0key._\\n\\n#### The Challenge: Cost vs. Performance in Kubernetes\\n\\nKubernetes workloads vary in their resource requirements. Some applications are **CPU-intensive**, requiring high compute power, while others are **memory-heavy**, needing more RAM to function efficiently. If you stick to a single instance type, you may\xa0either:\\n\\n1.  **Over-provision** of resources, leading to **wasted\xa0costs**.\\n2.  **Under-provision** resources, resulting in **performance issues**.\\n\\n#### Let us Understanding Hybrid Instance Strategies\\n\\nA **hybrid instance strategy** involves mixing different EC2 instance families based on workload needs. For\xa0example:\\n\\n*   **Compute-optimized instances (c7i.large):** Ideal for CPU-heavy applications.\\n*   **General-purpose instances (m7i.large):** Perfect for balanced workloads requiring a blend of CPU and\xa0memory.\\n\\nBy blending these instances, you avoid over-provisioning and ensure that each workload gets precisely the resources it\xa0needs.\\n\\n#### Our Workload Analysis: (example 3 microservices)\\n\\nImagine managing three critical microservices in an EKS\xa0cluster:\\n\\n> **_1\\\\. service-order_**\\n\\n**CPU Usage:** High (1819m per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Memory Usage:** Low (~1.3 GiB per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Best Fit:** c7i.large for compute efficiency.\\n\\n> **_2\\\\. service-user_**\\n\\n**CPU Usage:** Moderate (1830m per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Memory Usage:** Moderate (~2.4 GiB per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Best Fit:** c7i.large to optimize for CPU-bound processes.\\n\\n> **_3\\\\. service-search_**\\n\\n**CPU Usage:** High (1805m per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Memory Usage:** Moderate (~3.7 GiB per\xa0pod)\\n\\n**Best Fit:** m7i.large for a balanced approach.\\n\\n#### Why did Kubelancer, chose the Hybrid Approach\xa0Works?\\n\\nBy mixing **c7i.large** and **m7i.large** instances, we\xa0will:\\n\\n1.  **Reduce Costs:** Compute-optimized instances are cheaper for CPU-heavy tasks.\\n2.  **Right-Size Resources:** Memory-heavy applications get more memory-rich instances without wasting CPU capacity.\\n3.  **Ensure High Availability:** Multiple instance types provide fault tolerance and flexibility during provisioning.\\n\\n#### Performance & Cost\xa0Results\\n\\nAfter we implemented this hybrid strategy:\\n\\n*   **Resource Efficiency:** Workloads are provisioned based on exact resource\xa0needs.\\n*   **Cost Savings:** Reduced over-provisioning leads to lower monthly\xa0bills.\\n*   **Performance Gains:** High CPU workloads get dedicated compute-optimized nodes.\\n*   **Flexibility:** Karpenter\u2019s dynamic scaling ensures adaptability to traffic\xa0spikes.\\n\\n#### Karpenter, Every DevOps Engineer Infra Game\xa0Changer:\\n\\nAfter we implemented the Hybrid Instance Strategy for AWS EKS powered by Karpenter, it is a game-changer for our microservices cloud-native applications. we achieved cost savings, better resource utilisation, and enhanced performance.\\n\\nN\u200Dext Blog, Let us see how to implement\u2026.\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=5b7f9889b292)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45","source":"@site/blog/path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45.mdx","title":"Path Based - Simple Fanout Ingress on Kubernetes","description":"banner","date":"2025-01-10T12:21:31.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/tags/kubernetes"}],"readingTime":2.52,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Path Based - Simple Fanout Ingress on Kubernetes","slug":"path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45","date":"2025-01-10T12:21:31.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*PS5MQde3-QEiZJhK.jpg","tags":["Kubernetes"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Optimizing AWS EKS with Karpenter: A Hybrid Instance Strategy","permalink":"/blog/optimizing-aws-eks-with-karpenter-a-hybrid-instance-strategy-5b7f9889b292"},"nextItem":{"title":"Create AWS EKS Cluster\u200A\u2014\u200Aeksctl","permalink":"/blog/create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*PS5MQde3-QEiZJhK.jpg)\\n\\n\\n\\n### Simple fanout / Path Based Ingress -\xa0Demo\\n\\nExpose multiple services by using single IP\xa0address.\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*KvV_R2OD4Glgj3yq.png)\\n\\n#### Create three deployment and services.\\n\\n```\\nvi simplesite-deployment-services.yaml\\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: apps/v1  \\nkind: Deployment  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: home-deployment  \\nspec:  \\n  replicas: 1  \\n  selector:  \\n    matchLabels:  \\n      app: home  \\n  template:  \\n    metadata:  \\n      labels:  \\n        app: home  \\n    spec:  \\n      containers:  \\n        - name: home-container  \\n          image: kubelancer/simplehome:v1.0.0  \\n          ports:  \\n            - containerPort: 8080  \\n          env:                    \\n            - name: HOME\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://home-service:8080\\"  \\n            - name: BLOG\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://blog-service:8081\\"  \\n            - name: SERVICES\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://services-service:8082\\"  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: v1  \\nkind: Service  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: home-service  \\nspec:  \\n  selector:  \\n    app: home  \\n  ports:  \\n    - protocol: TCP  \\n      port: 8080  \\n      targetPort: 8080  \\n  type: ClusterIP  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: apps/v1  \\nkind: Deployment  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: blog-deployment  \\nspec:  \\n  replicas: 1  \\n  selector:  \\n    matchLabels:  \\n      app: blog  \\n  template:  \\n    metadata:  \\n      labels:  \\n        app: blog  \\n    spec:  \\n      containers:  \\n        - name: blog-container  \\n          image: kubelancer/simpleblog:v1.0.0  \\n          ports:  \\n            - containerPort: 8081  \\n          env:  \\n            - name: HOME\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://home-service:8080\\"  \\n            - name: BLOG\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://blog-service:8081\\"  \\n            - name: SERVICES\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://services-service:8082\\"  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: v1  \\nkind: Service  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: blog-service  \\nspec:  \\n  selector:  \\n    app: blog  \\n  ports:  \\n    - protocol: TCP  \\n      port: 8081  \\n      targetPort: 8081  \\n  type: ClusterIP  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: apps/v1  \\nkind: Deployment  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: services-deployment  \\nspec:  \\n  replicas: 1  \\n  selector:  \\n    matchLabels:  \\n      app: services  \\n  template:  \\n    metadata:  \\n      labels:  \\n        app: services  \\n    spec:  \\n      containers:  \\n        - name: services-container  \\n          image: kubelancer/simpleservices:v1.0.0  \\n          ports:  \\n            - containerPort: 8082  \\n          env:  \\n            - name: HOME\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://home-service:8080\\"  \\n            - name: BLOG\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://blog-service:8081\\"  \\n            - name: SERVICES\\\\_SERVICE\\\\_URL  \\n              value: \\"http://services-service:8082\\"  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: v1  \\nkind: Service  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: services-service  \\nspec:  \\n  selector:  \\n    app: services  \\n  ports:  \\n    - protocol: TCP  \\n      port: 8082  \\n      targetPort: 8082  \\n  type: ClusterIP\\n```\\n\\n*   Apply the deployment and\xa0services\\n\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f simplesite-deployment-services.yaml\\n```\\n\\n*   List deployment,pods,svc\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get deployment,pod,svc -o wide\\n```\\n\\n### Output\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*yPoTFoBcAttcNpHJ.png)\\n\\n### Create ingress (path-based)\\n\\n```\\nvi ingress-pathbased.yaml\\n```\\n```\\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1  \\nkind: Ingress  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: ingress-pathbased  \\n  namespace: default  \\nspec:  \\n  ingressClassName: nginx  \\n  rules:  \\n  - host: tify.kubelancer.com  \\n    http:  \\n      paths:  \\n      - path: /  \\n        pathType: Prefix  \\n        backend:  \\n          service:  \\n            name: home-service  \\n            port:  \\n              number: 8080  \\n      - path: /blog  \\n        pathType: Prefix  \\n        backend:  \\n          service:  \\n            name: blog-service  \\n            port:  \\n              number: 8081  \\n      - path: /services  \\n        pathType: Prefix  \\n        backend:  \\n          service:  \\n            name: services-service  \\n            port:  \\n              number: 8082\\n```\\n\\n*   Apply the\xa0ingress\\n\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f ingress-pathbased.yaml\\n```\\n\\n*   Get ingress\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get ingress\\n```\\n\\n### Output\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*PRVRH9bd79af6iBQ.png)\\n\\n### Validate\\n\\n**Home Page**\\n\\n```\\ncurl -i  --resolve tify.kubelancer.com:80:192.168.10.0 tify.kubelancer.com\\n```\\n\\n**Blog Page**\\n\\n```\\ncurl -i  --resolve tify.kubelancer.com:80:192.168.10.0 tify.kubelancer.com/blog\\n```\\n\\n**Services Page**\\n\\n```\\ncurl -i  --resolve tify.kubelancer.com:80:192.168.10.0 tify.kubelancer.com/services\\n```\\n\\n### Output\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*YlaQIXatCVO1wFl6.png)\\n\\nHome\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*1LBy3kHoMo37NSDp.png)\\n\\nBlog\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*sx01eIoGqGGWin5z.png)\\n\\nService\\n\\n### Happy Computing\xa0:)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=055e87a43b45)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b","source":"@site/blog/create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b.mdx","title":"Create AWS EKS Cluster\u200A\u2014\u200Aeksctl","description":"banner","date":"2025-01-10T12:18:39.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"AWS","permalink":"/blog/tags/aws"},{"inline":true,"label":"Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/tags/kubernetes"}],"readingTime":3.38,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Create AWS EKS Cluster\u200A\u2014\u200Aeksctl","slug":"create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b","date":"2025-01-10T12:18:39.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*8v3wYbI7g6dzqN5i.png","tags":["AWS","Kubernetes"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Path Based - Simple Fanout Ingress on Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/path-based-simple-fanout-ingress-on-kubernetes-055e87a43b45"},"nextItem":{"title":"Kubecost | Kubernetes cost monitoring and management","permalink":"/blog/kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*8v3wYbI7g6dzqN5i.png)\\n\\n### Create AWS EKS Cluster\u200A\u2014\u200Aeksctl\\n\\n\\n\\nCreating Kubenetes cluster in AWS have multiple options like using AWS SDK, Terraform, Cloudformation and easy and quick for new learner using AWS Console. In this blog we going see another well know method of creating AWS EKS cluster using \u201Ceksctl\u201D command by using as YAML configuration in default VPC. ( Same can be create by CLI command).\\n\\n### Let\u2019s get\xa0start\\n\\n### Prerequisites:\\n\\nLet install these binary one by\xa0one\\n\\n1.  AWS CLI\\n2.  eksctl CLI\\n3.  kubectl\\n\\n### Step 1. Install AWS CLI (Mac\xa0OS)\\n\\n### Download AWS CLI\xa0binary\\n\\n```\\ncurl \\"https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2.pkg\\" -o \\"AWSCLIV2.pkg\\"\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*6J25ADnX888KRIdU)\\n\\n### Install AWS\xa0CLI\\n\\n```\\nsudo installer -pkg ./AWSCLIV2.pkg -target /\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*J6P6L-2OHpXfbtX5)\\n\\n### Verify the installation\\n\\n```\\nwhich aws  \\naws --version\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/650/0*yE2erRuy89kWl4rF)\\n\\n### Step 2. Configure AWS\xa0CLI\\n\\n#### Step 2.1. Login to AWS console as root\xa0user\\n\\n#### Step 2.2. Create IAM\xa0user\\n\\n> username: kubedeveloper\\n\\n> No AWS console access, Only programmatic access\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*RHLvaEl4LgGfRTis)\\n\\nProvide Username\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*y0XglW3siyhLWF-h)\\n\\nPermission as per User\xa0Type\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*fz-rr7HCh2Qe0_PT)\\n\\n### Create Access and SecretAccessKey\\n\\n#### Step 2.3 Select the IAM user \u201Ckubedeveloper\u201D\\n\\n#### Step 2.4 Navigate to Security Credentials\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*W0FOS6LDMTBZfh_J)\\n\\n#### Step 2.5. Click Create access\xa0key\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*AZaS-aLEyZHx4rAT)\\n\\n#### Step 2.6 Select Use case\xa0:\\n\\n> **Command Line Interface (CLI) & check the Confirmation**\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*EsY2bE1Sk8lQZ-nq)\\n\\n#### Step 2.7. Set description tag\u200A\u2014\u200Aoptional and Click\xa0create\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*2DVs1_r_ae4rSSoF)\\n\\n> Now we got AccessKey and SecretAccessKey,\\n\\n#### Next, Let configure AWS CLI on Mac OS command\xa0line\\n\\n_Note: if multiple aws account configured, use\u200A\u2014\u200Aprofile_\\n\\n```\\n$ aws configure\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*UM7Vb_AAe_qqXXJ_)\\n\\n### Validate AWS CLI\xa0Access\\n\\n**Run any aws command to list resources**\\n\\n_Here eg: To list s3 buckets on my AWS\xa0account_\\n\\n```\\nbala@kubelancer Downloads % aws s3 ls\\n```\\n\\n### Getting output, which denoted AWS access has been configured correctly\\n\\n```\\nbala@kubelancer Downloads % aws s3 ls  \\n2022-12-13 21:36:02 firehose-backup-05bf6840\\n```\\n\\n### Install eksctl on Mac\xa0OS\\n\\n### To download the latest release, run on Mac OS (arm64 architecture):\\n\\n```\\ncurl -sLO \\"https://github.com/eksctl-io/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl\\\\_Darwin\\\\_arm64.tar.gz\\"  \\ntar -xzvf eksctl\\\\_Darwin\\\\_arm64.tar.gz  \\nsudo mv ./eksctl /usr/local/bin\\n```\\n\\n_Ref:_ [_https://www.weave.works/oss/eksctl/_](https://www.weave.works/oss/eksctl/?ref=blog.kubelancer.com)\\n\\n### Step 3: Creating an AWS EKS Kubernetes Cluster using eksctl\xa0tool\\n\\n#### 3.1. Create Cluster configuration yaml\xa0file\\n\\n```\\n$ vi cluster-config.yaml\\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: eksctl.io/v1alpha5  \\nkind: ClusterConfig  \\n  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: kubelancer-cluster-1  \\n  region: us-east-1  \\n  \\nnodeGroups:  \\n  - name: ng-1  \\n    instanceType: t4g.medium  \\n    desiredCapacity: 2  \\n    volumeSize: 20  \\n    ssh:  \\n      allow: false\\n```\\n\\n#### 3.2 Let\u2019s create eks cluster on aws using eksctl\xa0command\\n\\n```\\n$ eksctl create cluster -f cluster-config.yaml\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*bCHBjtkzz-9y-9zL.png)\\n\\nCluster created successfully\\n\\n_Note: if multiple aws account configured, use\u200A\u2014\u200Aprofile_\\n\\n### Get the cluster name by using eksctl\xa0command\\n\\n_eksctl interact with AWS API and get the required details from AWS\xa0cloud_\\n\\n```\\n$ eksctl get cluster --profile kubedev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*LdkIlcyQdjaZUq2B.png)\\n\\n### Use the following command to get update kube-config.\\n\\n```\\n$ aws eks update-kubeconfig --name=kubelancer-cluster-1 --region=us-east-1\\n```\\n\\n### Verify the\xa0Cluster\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get nodes\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*J5sncgvhxcyeRa4Q.png)\\n\\nCluster Node\xa0Status\\n\\n### Delete Cluster\\n\\n```\\n$ kubectl get poddisruptionbudget -A  \\n$ kubectl delete poddisruptionbudget coredns -n kube-system  \\n$ eksctl delete cluster -f cluster-config.yaml --profile kubedev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/700/0*az4ZrnhDpIqJNMBZ.png)\\n\\n### Happy Computing\xa0:)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=d7f548da3b1b)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13","source":"@site/blog/kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13.mdx","title":"Kubecost | Kubernetes cost monitoring and management","description":"banner","date":"2025-01-10T12:15:48.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"Kubernetes","permalink":"/blog/tags/kubernetes"}],"readingTime":1.6,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Kubecost | Kubernetes cost monitoring and management","slug":"kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13","date":"2025-01-10T12:15:48.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*F2lHnvP2bJ1onCOI.png","tags":["Kubernetes"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Create AWS EKS Cluster\u200A\u2014\u200Aeksctl","permalink":"/blog/create-aws-eks-cluster-eksctl-d7f548da3b1b"},"nextItem":{"title":"Setting up TLS with Nginx Ingress","permalink":"/blog/setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*F2lHnvP2bJ1onCOI.png)\\n\\n\\n\\n### Step 1: Create an AWS EKS\xa0Cluster\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get node\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*DRh29Vk83uMsRgo9)\\n\\n### Step 2: Enable Kubecost add-on using AWS\xa0CLI\\n\\n```\\naws eks create-addon --addon-name kubecost\\\\_kubecost --cluster-name kube-cluster-3 --region us-east-1\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*T5tS6u22Zrn87FJy)\\n\\n### Step 3: Deploying Kubecost on an Amazon EKS cluster using\xa0Helm\\n\\n**Step 3.1: Install Prerequisites**\\n\\n```\\neksctl create iamserviceaccount   \\\\\\\\  \\n    --name ebs-csi-controller-sa   \\\\\\\\  \\n    --namespace kube-system   \\\\\\\\  \\n    --cluster kube-cluster-3  \\\\\\\\  \\n    --attach-policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AmazonEBSCSIDriverPolicy  \\\\\\\\  \\n    --approve \\\\\\\\  \\n    --role-only \\\\\\\\  \\n    --role-name AmazonEKS\\\\_EBS\\\\_CSI\\\\_DriverRole  \\n      \\nexport_ SERVICE\\\\_ACCOUNT\\\\_ROLE\\\\_ARN=$(aws iam get-role --role-name AmazonEKS\\\\_EBS\\\\_CSI\\\\_DriverRole --output json | jq -r \'.Role.Arn\')\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*y_wUr-4OHjbej6cU)\\n\\n**Step 3.2: Install the Amazon EBS CSI add-on for EKS using the AmazonEKS\\\\_EBS\\\\_CSI\\\\_DriverRole**\\n\\n```\\neksctl create addon --name aws-ebs-csi-driver --cluster kube-cluster-3 \\\\\\\\  \\n    --service-account-role-arn $SERVICE\\\\_ACCOUNT\\\\_ROLE\\\\_ARN --force\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*gKQWV1UkQsiAaQLS)\\n\\n**Step 3.3: Install Kubecost on your Amazon EKS\xa0cluster**\\n\\n```\\nhelm upgrade -i kubecost \\\\\\\\  \\noci://public.ecr.aws/kubecost/cost-analyzer --version \\"1.104.4\\" \\\\\\\\  \\n\\\\--namespace kubecost --create-namespace \\\\\\\\  \\n\\\\-f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubecost/cost-analyzer-helm-chart/develop/cost-analyzer/values-eks-cost-monitoring.yaml\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*w9fkAIqW6rUf1mHe)\\n\\n### Step 4: Generate Kubecost dashboard endpoint using port-forward\\n\\n```\\nkubectl port-forward --namespace kubecost deployment/kubecost-cost-analyzer 9090\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*NTXPk7ZW2OBg5y1Q)\\n\\n### Step 5: Access Monitoring dashboards\\n\\n```\\nhttp://localhost:9090\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*HL9vl9iCQ_EgVI65)\\n\\n### Happy computing\xa0:)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=e0c27c8f5f13)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"},{"id":"setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe","source":"@site/blog/setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe.mdx","title":"Setting up TLS with Nginx Ingress","description":"banner","date":"2025-01-10T12:10:57.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":5.49,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Setting up TLS with Nginx Ingress","slug":"setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe","date":"2025-01-10T12:10:57.000Z","image":"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*6kJBVzwOvJqPKIMq.jpg","tags":[]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Kubecost | Kubernetes cost monitoring and management","permalink":"/blog/kubecost-kubernetes-cost-monitoring-and-management-e0c27c8f5f13"}},"content":"![banner](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*6kJBVzwOvJqPKIMq.jpg)\\n\\nThis guide provides a step-by-step tutorial on setting up TLS with Nginx Ingress on AWS EKS clusters using Let\u2019s-Encrypt\\n\\n\\n\\n> Expose a Kubernetes service with TLS using NGINX Ingress on AWS\xa0EKS\\n\\n### Step 1: Create an AWS EKS\xa0Cluster\\n\\n#### AWS EKS Kubernetes Cluster using \u201Ceksctl\u201D\xa0Command\\n\\n**1: Install AWS CLI (Mac\xa0OS)**\\n\\nDownload the AWS CLI\xa0binary\\n\\n```\\ncurl \\"https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2.pkg\\" -o \\"AWSCLIV2.pkg\\"\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*-uOW5dbmacOjPo2g.png)\\n\\n**2: Install**\\n\\n```\\nsudo installer -pkg ./AWSCLIV2.pkg -target /\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*NW75_hUcd60eyH3m.png)\\n\\n**3: Verify the installation**\\n\\n```\\nwhich aws  \\n  \\naws --version\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*Y7_4HvHCHsLx9dq7.png)\\n\\n**4: Configure AWS\xa0CLI**\\n\\nLogin to AWS console as root / Admin privileged IAM\xa0user\\n\\nCreate IAM\xa0user\\n\\n> username: kubedeveloper\\n\\n_No AWS console access, only programmatic access_\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*nYJgEgEPj6i1DEE8)\\n\\nUsername\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*SBWll94ycNQhprzo)\\n\\nUser permission\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*Ua4SvgzVeqSqV_oa)\\n\\nCreate user\\n\\n**5: Create Access and Secret Access\xa0Key**\\n\\n> Select the IAM user kubedeveloper\\n\\nNavigate to Security Credentials\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*zOto_jr2DEBgn9CC)\\n\\nCreate Security Credentials\\n\\nClick Create Access\xa0Key\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*h2a4aAInVUbvX4QP)\\n\\nAccess Key\\n\\nSelect Use case: Command Line Interface (CLI) & check the Confirmation\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*TzaVjLn0ORhPViI8)\\n\\nUse Case for Security Credentials\\n\\nSet description tag\u200A_\u2014\u200Aoptional_ and Click\xa0Create\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*eIih2cWjNPHnDpRR)\\n\\nDownload Credentials\\n\\n**6: Configure AWS CLI on Mac OS command\xa0line**\\n\\n```\\naws configure\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*iqMQk3TZIIzHOwYN.png)\\n\\n**7: Install eksctl on Mac\xa0OS**\\n\\nTo download the latest release, run on Mac OS (arm64 architecture):\\n\\n```\\ncurl -sLO \\"https://github.com/eksctl-io/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl\\\\_Darwin\\\\_arm64.tar.gz\\"  \\n  \\ntar -xzvf eksctl\\\\_Darwin\\\\_arm64.tar.gz  \\n  \\nsudo mv ./eksctl /usr/local/bin\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*TmucQJSTmo60PtPM.png)\\n\\nRef: [https://www.weave.works/oss/eksctl/](https://www.weave.works/oss/eksctl/?ref=blog.kubelancer.com)\\n\\n**8: Creating an AWS EKS Kubernetes Cluster using\xa0eksctl**\\n\\nCreate Cluster configuration YAML\xa0file\\n\\n```\\nvi cluster-config.yaml\\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: eksctl.io/v1alpha5  \\nkind: ClusterConfig  \\n  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: kubelancer-cluster-2  \\n  region: us-east-1  \\n  \\nnodeGroups:  \\n  - name: ng-1  \\n    instanceType: t4g.small  \\n    desiredCapacity: 2  \\n    volumeSize: 10  \\n    ssh:  \\n      allow: false\\n```\\n\\n**Let\u2019s create an EKS Cluster on AWS using eksctl\xa0command**\\n\\n```\\neksctl create cluster -f cluster-config.yaml\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*mS8EqU4eAODz6FE7.png)\\n\\nUse the following command to get kube-config context\\n\\n```\\naws eks update-kubeconfig --name=kubelancer-cluster-2 --region=us-east-1\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl get node\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*wZi3mNl5uKaQTsKY.png)\\n\\n### Step 2: Deploy the NGINX Ingress Controller\\n\\n1.  **Create Name space and\xa0deploy**\\n\\n```\\nkubectl create namespace ingress-nginx\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes/ingress-nginx/controller-v1.8.2/deploy/static/provider/cloud/deploy.yaml\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*UZWoNrOHQQeZX0tO)\\n\\nPre-flight check\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx\\n```\\n\\nOutput\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*xAbk68OS8iUUv17U)\\n\\nList Service\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get svc --namespace=ingress-nginx\\n```\\n\\n**Output**\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*P_-RpIxpmpf_11nL)\\n\\n### Step 3: Deploy a sample application\\n\\n1.  **Deploy sample app on dev namespace**\\n\\n```\\nkubectl create ns dev\\n```\\n```\\nvi kubewebserver.yaml  \\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: apps/v1  \\nkind: Deployment  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: kubewebserver  \\n  namespace: dev  \\n  labels:  \\n    app: kubewebserver  \\nspec:  \\n  replicas: 1  \\n  selector:  \\n    matchLabels:  \\n      app: kubewebserver  \\n  template:  \\n    metadata:  \\n      labels:  \\n        app: kubewebserver  \\n    spec:  \\n      containers:  \\n      - name: kubewebserver  \\n        image: kubelancer/hello-kubelancer:v1  \\n        ports:  \\n        - containerPort: 80  \\n\\\\---  \\napiVersion: v1  \\nkind: Service  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: kubewebserver-service  \\n  namespace: dev  \\n  labels:  \\n    app: kubewebserver-service  \\nspec:  \\n  type: ClusterIP  \\n  ports:  \\n  - port: 80  \\n    targetPort: 80  \\n    protocol: TCP  \\n  selector:  \\n    app: kubewebserver\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f kubewebserver.yaml\\n```\\n\\n**Output**\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get deploy,svc -n dev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*GvaKKz-fSlwg4eHi)\\n\\n### Step 4: Create ingress without\xa0TLS\\n\\n```\\nvi ingress-with-host.yaml\\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1  \\nkind: Ingress  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: ingress-with-host-02  \\n  namespace: dev  \\n  annotations:  \\n    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: /  \\nspec:  \\n  ingressClassName: nginx  \\n  rules:  \\n  - host: webtest.kubelancer.in  \\n    http:  \\n      paths:  \\n      - path: /  \\n        pathType: Prefix  \\n        backend:  \\n          service:  \\n            name: kubewebserver-service  \\n            port:  \\n              number: 80\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f ingress-with-host.yaml\\n```\\n\\n**Output**\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get ingress -n dev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*4dQ65fMQ1-9pA7zO)\\n\\nNote: Create CNAME record on your DNS for name resolution\\n\\n### Output\\n\\ncurl [http://webtest.kubelancer.in](http://webtest.kubelancer.in/?ref=blog.kubelancer.com)\\n\\n```\\ncurl http://webtest.kubelancer.in  \\nHello Kubelancer\\n```\\n\\n> Let we perform below steps to access same website using\xa0https://\\n\\n### To config SSL, we are going to use Cert-Manager and Let\u2019s Encrypt in this\xa0Lab\\n\\n_In simple:_\\n\\n### Cert Manager\\n\\ncert-manager creates TLS certificates for workloads in your Kubernetes, also helps to renew the certificate.\\n\\ncert-manager obtain certificates from a Let\u2019s\xa0Encrypt.\\n\\n### Let\u2019s Encrypt\\n\\nTo enable HTTPS for website, we need to purchase SSL certificate from Certificate Authority, which is costable. For demo or development environment, we have a choice to use free Certificate Authority (CA), that guy is Let\u2019s\xa0Encrypt.\\n\\n### Step 5: Deploy cert-manager\\n\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f https://github.com/cert-manager/cert-manager/releases/download/v1.14.4/cert-manager.yaml\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*_iO-ahE8W_vo9FwZ)\\n\\nOutput\\n\\n```\\nkubectl get pods --namespace cert-manager\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*tioJG98abrmVktZj)\\n\\n### Step 6: Configure a Let\u2019s Encrypt\xa0Issuer\\n\\n```\\napiVersion: cert-manager.io/v1  \\nkind: Issuer  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: letsencrypt-prod  \\n  namespace: dev  \\nspec:  \\n  acme:  \\n    server: https://acme-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory  \\n    email: noreply@gmail.com   \\n    privateKeySecretRef:  \\n      name: letsencrypt-prod  \\n    solvers:  \\n      - http01:  \\n          ingress:  \\n            ingressClassName: nginx\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl create -f issuer.yaml\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl get issuer -n dev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*joJyJnycikLrCPhN)\\n\\n> Note: Ensure the issuer is in Ready\xa0State\\n\\n### Step 7: Add TLS snippet on YAML and deploy Ingress\xa0Resource\\n\\n```\\nvi ingress-with-host.yaml\\n```\\n```\\napiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1  \\nkind: Ingress  \\nmetadata:  \\n  name: ingress-with-host-02  \\n  namespace: dev  \\n  annotations:  \\n    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: /  \\n    cert-manager.io/issuer: \\"letsencrypt-prod\\"  \\nspec:  \\n  ingressClassName: nginx  \\n  tls:  \\n  - hosts:  \\n    - webtest.kubelancer.in  \\n    secretName: kubewebserver-tls  \\n  rules:  \\n  - host: webtest.kubelancer.in  \\n    http:  \\n      paths:  \\n      - path: /  \\n        pathType: Prefix  \\n        backend:  \\n          service:  \\n            name: kubewebserver-service  \\n            port:  \\n              number: 80\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl apply -f ingress-with-host.yaml\\n```\\n```\\nkubectl get secret -n dev\\n```\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/0*hDcZwfUoNwoRwU7o)\\n\\n### Step 8:\xa0Output\\n\\n> Open in\xa0browser\\n\\n![image](https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1012/0*pCujpAIW_k7t5Hej.png)\\n\\nNow the website has secure connection\\n\\n#### Now the website has a secure encrypted connection using\xa0SSL\\n\\n### Happy Computing\xa0:)\\n\\n![image](https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=6bf68e329abe)\\n\\n---\\n\\n\u{1F449} Originally published on Medium: [Read more](https://bala-kubelancer.medium.com/setting-up-tls-with-nginx-ingress-6bf68e329abe?source=rss-2ce6e2575b1e------2)"}]}}')}}]);